message:
Hello, thanks for the great article!  
Now, I'm reading below article together and getting a glimpse of the difference between event-based & computing-based async operation.  
[https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/11/taskrun-etiquette-examples-dont-use.html](https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/11/taskrun-etiquette-examples-dont-use.html)

For the 1st event-driven TCS example, I would consume the TCS.Task with TaskAwaiter<t> in a main thread which is from method calling DoStuffAsync().

So, from this, may I ask you a question?

In the other article, you said that Task.Run should be fired in a main thread for a better efficiency. When you call 'DoStuffAsync()' and get an TaskAwaiter in a main thread, on which thread does this happen? Does it still fall into a category 'Conclusion: do not use Task.Run in the implementation of the method; instead, use Task.Run to call the method.'?

I'm considering below two scenarios.

// Below is an event-based approach  
class Program  
{  
 static void Main(string[] args)  
 {  
 Console.WriteLine("Hello");

 TaskAwaiter<int> awaiter = GetInt32().GetAwaiter();  
 awaiter.OnCompleted(() =>  
 {  
 Console.WriteLine(string.Format("The result is {0}", awaiter.GetResult()));  
 });

 Console.WriteLine("Start Non-blocking-calculation with TaskCompletionSource");  
 Console.ReadLine();  
 }

 static Task<int> GetInt32()  
 {  
 TaskCompletionSource<int> completionSource = new TaskCompletionSource<int>();  
 System.Timers.Timer timer = new System.Timers.Timer(5000);  
 timer.Elapsed += delegate  
 {  
 timer.Dispose();  
 completionSource.SetResult(42);  
 };  
 timer.Start();  
 return completionSource.Task;  
 }  
}

// Below is computing-based approach

class Program  
{  
 static void Main(string[] args)  
 {  
 Console.WriteLine("Hello");

 TaskAwaiter<int> awaiter = GetInt32().GetAwaiter();  
 awaiter.OnCompleted(() =>  
 {  
 Console.WriteLine(string.Format("Result is {0}", awaiter.GetResult()));  
 });  
 Console.WriteLine("Start Unblocking calculating");

 Console.ReadLine();  
 }

 static Task<int> GetInt32()  
 {  
 Task<int> my_task = Task.Run(() =>  
 {  
 Thread.Sleep(5000);  
 return 42;  
 });  
 return my_task;  
 }  
}
